title: Remarks by SHWF on backyard poultry and court ruling on claims by public doctors
content_text:
p>
Following is a transcript (English portion) of remarks made by the Secretary for 
Health, Welfare and Food, Dr York Chow, at a media session at the Legislative 
Council Building today (March 1): Reporter: Can I have your reaction to the High Court's ruling? Dr Chow: First of all, we respect the judgment of the court. Certainly, I think 
this is an opportunity now for the Hospital Authority to communicate with the 
public doctors to settle on the working conditions and hopefully to improve 
their morale. I think the working conditions of young doctors, particularly, has

their morale. I think the working conditions of young doctors, particularly, has 
always been an issue that needs to be settled. Reporter: Would you ask the new Chief Executive of the Hospital Authority to 
conduct an urgent review on doctors' working hours? Dr Chow: I think the Hospital Authority has conducted a review on the working 
conditions and working hours of young doctors recently. They have also been 
engaging with the Public Doctors' Association on a regular basis. So I think the 
Chief Executive of course needs to take up the role of the main communicator and

Chief Executive of course needs to take up the role of the main communicator and 
contact person with the Public Doctors' Association. I'm sure that he would take 
time to understand the situation and also to implement suitable policy for the 
future. Reporter: Now there is a judicial review launched against the Government on 
backyard farming, would you reconsider paying farmers of backyard poultry for 
compensation? Dr Chow: I think the legal argument on compensation has been very clear, as far 
as the Government is concerned. We would not like to comment any further since

as the Government is concerned. We would not like to comment any further since 
the case is now in court. I don't think we should comment until there is a 
judgment. Reporter: I just don't understand that the number of backyard poultry is very 
small, why doesn't the Government pay off the farmers? Dr Chow: I don't want to comment now because the case is already in court. I 
don't think my comment will be fair at this stage. (Please also refer to the
